    </div>
  </div></div><h2>What most agencies won’t tell you (pitfalls to avoid)</h2><p>Not everything makes it into the sales pitch. Here are some of the most common surprises SaaS founders encounter after signing with a mobile application design agency:</p><ul role="list"><li><strong>Hidden costs</strong></li></ul><p>That $50K quote? It might not include UX research, usability testing, or dev handoff prep. Some agencies charge extra for what should be table stakes. </p><p>As one Reddit user <a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/UXDesign/comments/1fw5mo7/how_much_does_it_cost_to_get_an_entire_app/">noted</a>, “<em>There is also an additional cost for branding</em>.” So always ask what’s included and get it in writing.</p><figure style="max-width:1999pxpx" class="w-richtext-align-fullwidth w-richtext-figure-type-image"><div><img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/5f16d69f1760cdba99c3ce6e/680f59413181ac7bccfcc40f_80.png" loading="lazy" alt="Reddit reviews"/></div></figure><ul role="list"><li><strong>Junior or outsourced designers</strong></li></ul><p>Some agencies pitch you with their A-team and then hand your project off to a junior, or worse, a white-labeled freelancer overseas. Suddenly, your product looks like a group project.</p><p>Reddit users often point out the same issue<strong>, </strong>“<em>So many agencies these days simply outsource to low cost freelancers anyways</em>.”</p><figure style="max-width:1999pxpx" class="w-richtext-align-fullwidth w-richtext-figure-type-image"><div><img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/5f16d69f1760cdba99c3ce6e/680f5960ecbf211ec97b8e72_81.png" loading="lazy" alt="Reddit reviews"/></div></figure><ul role="list"><li><strong>Pretty ≠ useful</strong></li></ul><p>Plenty of agencies can deliver something stunning on Dribbble. But if they don’t ask product questions about onboarding, retention, or feature prioritization, you’ll end up with a sleek UI that confuses users.</p><p>One Redditor summed it up perfectly, “<em>So, any place that is still working on a &#x27;pixel perfect&#x27; methodology means it&#x27;s a place that has a UX/UI team that still doesn&#x27;t really &#x27;get&#x27; the medium</em>.”</p><figure style="max-width:1999pxpx" class="w-richtext-align-fullwidth w-richtext-figure-type-image"><div><img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/5f16d69f1760cdba99c3ce6e/680f59709e22e49bf08f3b00_82.png" loading="lazy" alt="Reddit reviews"/></div></figure><ul role="list"><li><strong>Feedback friction</strong></li></ul><p>Some teams follow strict sprint schedules or lock feedback into set phases. That’s fine for big orgs. For startups that iterate fast? It’s a bottleneck.</p><p>This Redditor <a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/graphic_design/comments/11a23r3/design_veterans_does_the_feedback_process_ever/">puts</a> it, “<em>The kinda unsaid or unappreciated requirement of a GD is taking constant feedback; criticism is part of the job, everyone of your individual projects, not something most professions have built in</em>…”</p><figure style="max-width:1999pxpx" class="w-richtext-align-fullwidth w-richtext-figure-type-image"><div><img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/5f16d69f1760cdba99c3ce6e/680f597c6e59390041c8fc3e_83.png" loading="lazy" alt="Reddit reviews"/></div></figure><p>These aren’t deal-breakers but red flags worth spotting before the contract is signed. Next, we’ll explain how to select the <a href="best-ux-agencies">best UX agencies</a> for your needs.</p><h2>How to choose the right agency for you</h2><p>By now, you’ve seen what different mobile app design companies offer and what they don’t tell you. Let’s make your choice a little easier.</p><p>Here’s how to match agency type to your startup’s current needs:</p><h4>✔ Early-stage SaaS?</h4><p>You need speed, clarity, and a team that understands product thinking. Go with <strong>Eleken</strong>. We won’t overload you with processes and know how to move fast without breaking UX.</p><h4>✔ Need branding, design, and development in one place?</h4><p>If you’re building something big and want a one-stop shop, check out <strong>Ramotion or Blue Label Labs</strong>. But expect to pay more and move slower, which is not a great fit if you&#x27;re bootstrapping.</p><h4>✔ Building something complex (AI, VR, or enterprise-grade)?</h4><p>You’ll need specialized skills, compliance, and technical scale. Look at <strong>Hedgehog Lab</strong> or <strong>Appinventiv. </strong>They’re built for this level, just don’t expect lean startup speed.</p><h4>✔ Need polish?</h4><p>Your product is functional, but it looks rough. Consider a freelancer or <strong>Eleken’s subscription model</strong> to clean up the UX, redesign your app, or for a UX/UI audit.</p><h4>✔ On a tight budget?</h4><p>You probably don’t need an agency yet. Explore no-code tools, white-label solutions, or individual contractors. <a href="best-ux-agencies">Top UI/UX design agencies</a> are great, but they’re not cheap. Rushing into one can cost more money than it saves.</p><div class="w-embed"><div class="banner-wrap banner">
    <div class="banner-row">
      <div class="bann-col">
